HEADWORD: Hemeralopia
<hw>Hem`e*ra*lo"pi*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr.
Gr. <?/, the opposite of <?/; <?/ day + <?/ of <?/. See
<er>Nyctalopia</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A disease of the
eyes, in consequence of which a person can see clearly or without pain
only by daylight or a strong artificial light; day sight.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Some writers (as Quain) use the word in the opposite
sense, <it>i. e.</it>, day blindness. See
<er>Nyctalopia</er>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hemerobian</ent>⟦br⟧
